snippet: The demise of St. Vincent’s Hospital in Greenwich Village two years ago has led to a struggle for health care supremacy, offering a glimpse at what might be the future of urban medicine.
abstract: Demise of St Vincent’s Hospital in Greenwich Village in 2010 has led to a struggle for health care supremacy in Lower Manhattan, offering a glimpse at what might be the future of urban medicine; walk-in clinics are filling hospital's void, hoping to show they are more efficient and consumer-friendly than a hospital-based system; some are already forming relationships with hospitals.
lead_paragraph: The demise of St. Vincent’s Hospital in Greenwich Village two years ago has led to a struggle for health care supremacy, offering a glimpse at what might be the future of urban medicine.

headline.seo: After Losing St. Vincent’s Hospital, Manhattan Sees Rise in Clinic Care
